ngelicals.The Holy Vote shows, however, that the church continues to uphold already privileged identities even as it reworks its messages to appear more welcoming, offering insight into how White evangelical understandings about sex and families have shaped a political movement that has helped remake the Republican Party and transform American politics. In this enlightening work, Diefendorf highlights the complex origins of these understandings and considers their intersections with contemporary culture and enduring social inequalities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAnxietyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aAnxietyzUnited States. 0aChristianity and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aChristians, WhitezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aEqualityxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975958?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975958/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY